title: Prusa i3 extruder modified for MK8

description.text:
This is a modified version of the Prusa i3 x-carriage and extruder. The prusa uses a smaller gear than commonly available, which results in misalignment with the hotend entry when used with those common parts. This version has the motor shifted 0.875mm (the holes shown in the section view are usually vertically aligned), to accommodate a gear with effective diameter of 7mm (like MK8). The x-carriage is also included, as one of the motor holes is shared with the motor.

Other changes are,
1) added a fitting input to use a PTFE tube for filament input (suitable for M6, I usually use a tap to cut the thread)
2) removed the PINDA probe mount (I prefer to correctly level the bed)
3) various tweaks for hole sizes, and for hex nuts only (no square nuts)

The best orientation for printing each part should be obvious. I have closed holes that will need bridging for best print quality, so a drill bit will need to be run through those holes.

This aide is applicable to Quadriplegic users that have no finger mobility, but that still retain arm/wrist mobility.

This pin that can slip into a normal OT sleeve. An OT sleeve is a material strap that attaches around the palm, and has a sleeve inside for slipping a spoon/knife (or stylus) into.

An apple pencil or regular stylus can then be attached. Please note that due to the conductive requirement of most stylus and phone, it is important that the stylus still touches the person fingers in order to conduct.

So you will need:
1) This model printed out.
2) OT sleeve
3) A stylus compatible with your device, and that can fit into the clip.
(You may need to scale the model up or down a bit if your stencil is wider/narrower)

I have uploaded a Lefthand and Righthand version.

I have two quadriplegic friends who use this gadget daily for accessing their phone.

I also add a pin-stick with a platform. You can either velcro or superglue this part to your phone's cover to hold in the other hand.

I also add a microphone platform. Again you can simply stick a phone-cover to this flat surface (or use Velcro). For this one you will need to go buy a microphone screw-top that fits your particular microphone stand, and then replace the top half with the platform.

Also see:

across the heatbed & the part being printed.

The MK2S design installs to the outside of the fan using the existing
screws. There are 2 versions, a half cover and a full cover. I've only
used the half cover and it works very well but included both versions
should you care to try either.

The MK3 has 4 versions. Two of them are "push-fit"( no screw holes),
one is a half cover and the other is full. The other two versions are
similar(1 half, 1 full) but have two screw holes. I've only used the
half cover sans holes version so far and I'm quite happy with the
results.

[I also have a couple generic(plain) designs for 40mm fans as well should anyone like...I can upload those as well.]

This is a AID toolkit for Occupational Therapy for Quadriplegic or limited-hand-mobility cases.

These are building blocks that we use to decide what can work for your particular case.

Blocks/Shapes of different angles can be stuck together until a good combination is found.

The 90degree bracket is meant to go inside the hand. And the finger-shape can be stuck onto that using the appropriate angled block.

You can print rings and holders at different scales until you find the correct size for the hands/fingers you are working with.

So pick the parts, find the right scale for your application, and you can construct many different combinations of utilities.

We have had success with finger-stilts, and with a knife-mount for cutting, and general waterbottle handle. These are all modular parts-based so you can scale and print just the appropirate bits and then stick them together. We usually use prestik first... and then once we think it can work we stick it down with proper glue.

The platform can be used with velcro-straps to attache around the palm of the hand.

I will add to the kit as we go. There are more things we are trying.

title: Power Supply Unit PSU Cover for Prusa i3 for use with S-240-12 PSU from China

description.text:
If you want to mount one of the widely available Power Supply Units to an original Prusa printer, this part is for you.

Mounting a S-240-12 PSU (this is the standard $20 cheap Chinese power supply widely available) to the original Prusa frame is moderately difficult with this PSU cover. It is based on the original Prusa i3 PSU cover, with the dimensions adjusted for the inexpensive PSU. The only difficulty involves drilling and tapping two 4 mm threads in the PSU aluminum housing.

Printer:

Anet A8

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2 mm

Infill:

20%

Notes:

Wall thickness 1.2 mm, this makes the cover pretty sturdy.

Electrical wiring

The PSU cover is designed to be used with a power socket with integrated fuse holder and an illuminated power switch.

You need these components:

  • 1A fuse
  • 27x31mm hole power socket with 36mm mounting holes, e.g. "EKS 01 S" available as "KES 2SI" at www.reichelt.de
  • 20x13mm power switch, e.g. Marquardt 1800.1108, available at www.reichelt.de as "WIPPE 1800.1108"
  • Insulated crimp spade connectors for connecting to PSU terminals
  • 4.8mm crimp connectors (more commonly used automotive 6.3mm connectors work as well)
  • some 2.5mm wire (red, black) for low voltage wiring
  • some 1.5mm wire (brown, blue, yellow/green) for high voltage wiring

Mount the socket using two M3x10 countersunk screws and M3 nuts. Isolate the high voltage wiring well, I used isolated crimp spade terminals for the PSU connections and clear isolating covers for the high voltage terminals. Alternatively you can solder the wiring and use shrink wrap for isolation.

Mechanical mounting

The PSU is attached to the cover using two M3 screws:

  • Insert a M3 nut in the cover's nut trap
  • Use one M3x10 hex head screw with a small washer to fasten the PSU to the cover. Use the access hole opposite the nut trap to get to the screw
  • Use one M3x10 counter sunk screw to fasten the other side of the PSU.

Now hold the PSU to the frame and mark the upper mounting bolt location using a drill (by hand, not in a machine! We just want to mark at this point!). It is important to start with the upper hole!

Drill the PSU housing using a 3 mm drill. Make sure no metal gets into the PSU!!! Now cut a 4mm thread. You may drill through the heat sink inside the PSU, this is no problem.

Mount the PSU using the upper hole and a 4mm bolt. Now mark the lower hole again using a drill, remove PSU and drill using 3mm drill and cut 4mm thread. Make sure no metal gets into the PSU!!

Now you can mount the PSU to the frame and mount the PSU to the Y-part of the frame as well. I have slightly elongated the holes to allow for tolerances when drilling the PSU.

Modifying the design

I wanted to use the Chinese PSU I got off eBay, and still wanted to preserve the original Prusa look, and I think it turned out nicely.

It took me a few tries to get this perfect. I removed the "Prusa3D" writing from the cover because my print didn't turn out nice. You can easily comment it back in in the SCAD file.

Derived from "Squashball Feet" by kaktus2 (see link on this page), this is a redesign using OpenSCAD to generate the STL. Kudos to kaktus2 for the original idea and implementation. I wanted to get away from the (slightly) fragile arms of the original, and I found that a solid ring was good enough to hold the ball, and yet still allow its insertion. This version does not need to be printed solid; the one shown in the pictures uses 10% infill and it's quite sturdy. I used a two-part print to get the colour band; the idea is to keep the "racing stripe" theme of the CR-10 going. To do two-colour prints, set your slicer to end the first part ("stop printing at height") at Z = 22.10 mm. Print that, and when it ends swap in the new filament colour and cycle the extruder a bit so all the old colour is gone. Then print the second part with the slicer set with Z starting ("start printing at height") at 22.10 mm. Easy as! Of course you can just print in one go, in one colour.

Squash is an actual sport. It's fast and exhausting. Look it up! I played it a lot, in my youth. To complete this build you will need one squash ball per part you print. Use a yellow-dot ball if you can - these are softer and less inflated.

This design seems to have dramatically reduced resonance and noise from my printer which was sitting on a wood desk on a wood floor. I think there has been a slight improvement (i.e., reduction in ringing ... ghosting... in the prints it produces, too).

I'm including the OpenSCAD source file. It's a real quick hack, and not pretty at all. But it's there so you can see how it's done and modify it if you need to. Apologies for the lack of comments.

comments.text: No, I don't think it will work as well with racquet balls. The reason is, squash balls (especially yellow-dot) do not bounce well at all. They are effectively dead-flat.  Drop one from (say) a couple of metres height, and it might bounce few centmetres. The only bounce once they've been warmed up by really vigorous hitting. The colour of the dots indicate the pressure inside the ball, and hence the bounciness. Yellow-dots are for professional players and bounce the least.  The whole point is, low pressure to do the best job of dampening vibration. I suspect racquet balls are quite bouncy, certainly much more so than squash balls. So I doubt that they will work as effectively.

description.text:
Hail Lightbringers!

I tried to find the perfect insert for my Massive Darkness game. I backed the kickstarter and received a looooooot of miniatures.

What i got:

  • Massive Darkness core box
  • Lightbringer Pack
  • Enemy Box: Troglodytes
  • Enemy Box: Ratlings
  • Noble Warriors vs The Cockatrix
  • Bloodmoon Assassins vs The Hellephant
  • Sorceres vs. Lord Tusk
  • 3D Pack: Chests & Pillars
  • Black Plague Crossover Set
  • Plastic Token Set

I found a well designed solution for all the cards included in the game and printed them in green (https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2559346). To store my miniatures i started to design my own things. Right now the thing is work in progess, but i wanted to show you the current status and would like to get your feedback.

Here is a list of the prototype:

  1. Lowest layer:

    • Original tiles (9x)
    • Token box 1 (3D Chests & plastic wound tokens)
    • Token box 2 (plastic level tokens & plastic exit token & plastic artifact/lair tokens & plastic first player token & palstic starting zone token & hero color bases/pegs)

  2. Second layer:

    • enemy box 1 (Heroes (Core Heroes (6x) & Kickstarter Heroes (3x) & Noble Warrios box Heroes (3x) & Sorcerer box Heroes (3x) & Bloodmoon Assassins Heros box (3x) )
    • enemy box 2 (Roaming Monsters)
    • enemy box 3 (Hellephant & Giant Spider & Unicorn & Goblin/Dwarf/Oric Agent & Dark Bridges (2x))
    • Token box (door tokens (15x) & pillar 3D tokens (6x) & 24 dice in dice bag
    • hero dashboards (6x) ALTERNATIV: Hero Box (Same box with "Heroes" text in in)
    • class sheets (1x per Hero (used to laminate them)
  3. Top layer:
    • (2x) roaming monster box
    • roaming monster box small (Lord Tusk & cockatrix box)
    • (2x) enemy box 4 half or enemy box 4 (Goblin Warriors (2x Boss and 16x Goblin Warriors) (Goblin Archers (2x Boss and 16x Goblin Archers) Orc Flayers, Goblin Archers, Orc Enforcers)
    • enemy box 5 (Dwarf Defenders, Dwarf Warriors)
    • (2x) enemy box 6 (roaming monster, ratlings, troglodytes
  • rulebook

What is not included:

  • The extra tiles (lava & crystal tiles)
  • Lava & Crystal Campaign
  • One of the Lightbringer boxes (the one with the "Cliffbreaker Cyclops" in it)

Notes:

The first layer token boxes do not fit for the original tokens, only for the plastic versions!
I am going to design a solution for the Monster & Hero Boxes for upcoming add-ons.

The connectors on the X52 /Pro are a bit flimsy. This holds them in place and protects them from bending/damaging.

Print slowly and prevent blobs at all costs (enable coasting, retraction, ..). The fit is not too tight, but if it is for you, just scale up the "base" part slighlty.

Assembly

Stick the base part to the x52 with (thin!) double sided tape.

For easy alignment, put the connector through the base hole and connect it to the X52 first. The base part is now dangling from the cable.
Now connect the plug part to the base part (cable goes through slot) and push the assembly over the connector until it sticks to the X52.

Goes without saying: befor applying the tape, clean the surfaces with alcohol!

(Re-) Connection

Its easiest to always plug the connector into the X52 first and then slide the protection over the connector and twist-lock it to the base part.

description.text:
I recently got into sculpting miniatures after watching tom mason on YouTube. so i decided to invent a thing to make it more convenient. i have included all the STL files in parts so it is fully customisable and they are in the correct orientation for printing. i have also included the editable 123d design files.
i designed this around my own hand, and threes ample space for me to hold it, my hands are average sized, it should fit most peoples hands, unless you have really big hands you may need to widen the "main plate" file. depending on if you're left or right handed will decide which way up you fit the "main plate" to the handle, the far side is wider than the part where your thumb would sit, as when your hand is in a gripping/fist shape, the knuckles stick out further.

Its kind of a pallet for sculpting, like a painter would use.

it comes with 10 tool pots which are removable so all your favourite tools. it also comes with a rolling pin which has a little storage space inside the handle for easy access.

the rolling pin guides are interchangeable so you can roll putty/clay at varying thicknesses. staring at 0 an going up to 1mm thick in 0.2mm increments. you can expand these further if needed, just edit the "pin guide" file. it inst as cumbersome as it looks and you're able to comfortably see your armature at any angle you'd need without tools slipping out.

I printed this entire thing with just 10% infill and it is ample strong enough, all except the rolling pin, if i were to print it again id do 100% infill, it feels a little weak where it sits on the guide rails at just 10%. but if you have the time, more infill is obviously better!

I plan on making textured rolling pins and adding to the files in the future, only reason i haven't done it already is my hard drive is dying in my computer, once i get a new one, ill add a whole bunch of different textured rolling pins.

I think thats all i need to say, any questions or suggested edits feel free to ask!

oh yeah, while im here, ill take the time to shamelessly advertise my facebook group. its a place for budding mini sculptors to get together and talk minis and sculpting. Join us!

This is a very simple SCAD file used for generating XY grids for calibration testing.

Printing note: unless you set a high enough margin print without skirt and brim!

Customization info

All relevant parameters are customizable - the bed size, margins (gap between bed edges and the grid), layer height and width and also the multiplier that says how many "holes" there will be per dimension. The script also supports different X and Y dimensions (in case your bed's height and width are different). Margins for each dimension can also be set separately.

Example STL parameters

The example .stl is generated for printers with bed size of 200x200mm with multiplier set to 4 (thus generating 16 "holes"), 1mm margins, layer height of 0.2mm and line width (extruder size) of 0.4mm.

How is the grid generated?

The grid is generated by first creating a big block and then subtracting all the "holes", which (in theory) results in better geometry than adding all the "rows" and "columns" together like a table.

title: Creality CR-10 MINI Strain relief bracket for heated bed cable
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is a remake of Greg191134 Creality CR-10 Strain relief bracket for heated bed cable but for the CR-10 Mini.

I completely redesigned the bracket to suit the slightly larger cable and clip on the CR-10 Mini. I didn't actually use Gregs files but took inspiration from his design.

This an accessory for the Creality CR-10 Mini 3D Printer.

The purpose of this bracket is to hold the wires for the heated bed in place to avoid that they wiggle when the bed move which would ultimately lead to breaking the welds or the wires.
The bracket is designed to be installed on the far left screw under the spring as shown on one of the picture. You will typically need to remove the glass bed for that.

The bracket does not touch the heated bed and can be safely printed in PLA.

Once the bracket is in place, move the wires a bit toward the bed (to avoid to put too much tension in them) and hold the wire in place with 2 zip ties.

description.text:
(Deutscher Text: Siehe unten...)

Do you know those deodorant bottles with a spherical cap?
They are a perfect example for form not following function!

Having them upright is a terrible waste of time in the morning, especially when they're half-empty - or half-full, depending on your view on that kind of things: you have to wait till the fluid on the inside hat reached the roll-on ball ....

So I designed this simple upside-down stand.
This is the cylindrical version for the "Beyersdorf" products, like "NIVEA".

There is also a purist cubic version online: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2743147
And there is a customizer online: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2743081

Enjoy, and let me know when you've made one, and what it looks like!
Photos are from an early prototype!

[DE:]

Ich nutze diese Deo-Roll-On's, die einen halbkugelförmigen Deckel haben. Das Design der Verpackung ist ein perfektes Gegenbeispiel zu "Form folgt Funktion": Sobald die Flasche nur noch halbleer (oder halbvoll) ist, dauert es eine gefühlte Ewigkeit, bis der Inhalt an der Kugel angekommen ist - vor allem morgens, wenn der Kopf noch nicht so schnell ist ;-)
Durch den runden Deckel lässt sich die Fasche aber nicht kopfüber lagern.

Ich habe diesen einfachen Ständer entworfen, mit dem sich Deo-Roll-On's kopfüber lagern lassen. Passt für die Produkte der Firma Beyersdorf, wie z.B. "Nivea". Die Fotos sind von einer frühen Prototyp-Phase

Es gibt auch eine "puristisch-kubistische" Variante.: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2743147.

(Deutscher Text: Siehe unten...)

Do you know those deodorant bottles with a spherical cap?
They are a perfect example for form not following function!

Having them upright is a terrible waste of time in the morning, especially when they're half-empty - or half-full, depending on your view on that kind of things: you have to wait till the fluid on the inside hat reached the roll-on ball ....

So I designed this simple upside-down stand.
There are two main designs: a cubic or a cylindrical body. Those can be mixed-and-matched wit a square or circular base plate.
There is also a purist cubic version online: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2743147
And there is a ready-made cylindrical version: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2743048

Enjoy, have fun remixing it and let me know when you've made one, and what it looks like!

Das Design der Verpackung ist ein perfektes Gegenbeispiel zu "Form folgt Funktion": Sobald die Flasche nur noch halbleer (oder halbvoll) ist, dauert es eine gefühlte Ewigkeit, bis der Inhalt an der Kugel angekommen ist - vor allem morgens, wenn der Kopf noch nicht so schnell ist ;-)

Ich habe diesen einfachen Ständer entworfen, mit dem sich Deo-Roll-On's kopfüber lagern lassen.
Der Customizer erlaubt die Auswahl zwischen zwei prinzipiellen Designs: kubisch oder zylindrisch. Diese beiden lassen sich wahlweise mit einer kreisförmigen oder einer quadratischen Bodenplatte kombinieren.

Es gibt auch eine "puristisch-kubistische" Variante.: https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2743147.

description.text:
Repteier Firmware for Geeetech G2S based on WBRUCEM https://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1301129

Modifications:

- PWM fan used to cool the printed object - needs rewiring of the fan cabling - see: website bechele.de
- Autoleveling activated and configured
- Autoleveling area reduced to 3 x 3 steps with only two repeats each.
- Autoleveling positions swapped to prevent of mechanical crash after levelling when homing.
- Preparation for printing ABS with temperatures up to 260 °
- Enabling of EEPROM use - Note: !! You need to send a M502 command once after software Upload to make Autoleveling work !!
- Reduced the number of subsegments to get enough ram for runnig autolevelling.

This isn't a printable thing. It is a starting configuration for running Repetier-Firmware on the Geeetech Delta G2S printer. Many thanks to WBRUCEM for the great piece of work.

For more information visit:
[bechele.de - english] (http://bechele.de/pages/english/126-0.html)
[bechele.de - german] (http://bechele.de/pages/german/135-0.html)
To use:
Go to [https://www.repetier.com/firmware/dev/index.php]
Upload the enclosed .json file as your "old" configuration.
Complete the configuration tool steps, adjusting where needed to match YOUR printer.
At the end, choose "Download complete firmware" to retrieve the entire firmware package (.zip file).
Compile and upload to your printer as you have done with Marlin.
Further configuration changes should always be performed via the online configuration tool. DON'T edit your Configuration.h file directly.

Notes:

Pay attention to the diagram showing how to measure dimensions of your printer. Some of these may differ slightly from the ones used in Marlin.
Extruder offsets are handled entirely within the firmware. You should enter ZERO offsets in your slicer and Repetier-Host configurations.
This firmware is under active development. If you happen to download a copy that fails to compile, just try again after a couple of days. Chances are the problem will have been fixed.

This my collection of clips for a Garmin Oregon handheld GPS unit.

title: SteelSeries Sensei Side Buttons
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
After a little under 4 years of use, the left side buttons on my SteelSeries Sensei broke. I took it apart and designed a replacement part.

If you need to replace your right side buttons, just mirror the model on the Z axis in your slicer, lay one of the 2 top pegs flat on the bed and you're ready to go.

Tronxy X1

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Resolution:

0.1 mm

Infill:

30%

Notes:

The support settings I used for this print are as follows:

  • 20% support infill
  • 2 dense support layers at 40% infill
  • Support infill angles: -45° and 45°
  • Upper vertical separation layers: 2

Taking apart the mouse to replace your buttons is fairly easy. You'll need only a screwdriver with a Philips 2.5 head and some way of peeling the skates, such as an xacto knife.

To open the case, take a look at the start of the following video: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yxRrpD_ewpE.

Once you popped the mouse open, remove the 3 screws that hold the circuit board for the side buttons in place and remove it carefully.

Locate your broken button set, slide it out vertically and replace it with the new one. Put everything back together and you're done!

description.text:
I designed this to replace the metal hinges on my camper van conversion, for the cupboard where the gas bottle is held. The problem being that the gas bottle will only just fit through the door opening and the door gets in the way even when open, preventing the gas bottle being swapped without unscrewing the hinge from the inside of the cupboard.

So, I designed a hinge that would mount in the same place and work in the same way normally but had a quick release lever that would allow the door (and part of the hinge) to be removed and replaced quickly, easily and without tools.

The cam locking mechanism also allows the hinge length to be adjusted in a similar way to the original metal version.

It's a standard 35mm dia concealed hinge fitting although this is the Blind Corner type where the door sits flush with the cupboard when closed and at 90 degrees plus when opened.

I will probably do a modified version that could replace the more normal corner hinge at some point.

It will need 2 M3 x 20mm cap head bolts and m3 nuts to assemble. All the dimensions are defined as parameters at the top of the file if anyone wants to customise it to suit their own purposes.

v1.0.1 - Thickened up the outer supports on the fixed plate to add strength after one failed when operating the cam lever to lock the hinge.

Notes:

Assuming you print using the default "printing" layout for the .stl, You will need to use supports for the cup and in Cura I just use the supports form the build bed option.

I printed mine in PETG as it's more durable than PLA although PLA would probably be OK.

Recently I made an airguard for my printer, since I experienced differences with my prints depending on the different directions on my printbed.
I was quite satisfied with the result, but I'm not sure, if it made a real difference.
At least it also worked as a protection from getting burned fingers, so with the intention of making a fanduct for active cooling of prints, I decided to combine my initial design with an enhanced model, that takes into account, that a 40x40 mm fan should be attached.

Printer:

Geeetech i3 Pro X

Rafts:

Yes

Supports:

Yes

Infill:

30%

Notes:

Printed at 250 degrees C and 70 degress C on heatbed.
Clear PETG.

Thoughts about the design

As the pictures shows, I aimed for as little impact on the physical dimensions as possible, and I didn't want to compromise my X-axis by building something on the side.
So my hotend has the original cooler sitting unaffected, and the weight of the secondary cooler is so little, that it shouldn't affect neither the movements or the stress on the 2 screws fixing the whole unit to my hotend.

The nozzle is sitting 1,5 mm below the fanduct, so it's still the closest part to the heatbed.
I haven't calculated anything about the airflow, but I designed the holes, so none of them have direct air pushed through, which could bring me back to square 1.
My fan can deliver 11 m3 per hour, so I'm pretty sure I'll never have to run cooling at more than 25-50% during prints, but I feel confident about the overall ability to perform in any scenario.
The holes are directed to avoid cooling the hotend but at the same time they hit the printing part as directly as I could design it.
